Reproducible Workflows

Lynda Boothroyd

30/08/2019

Once you have your dataprocessing and analyses written in r code, an advantage to RMarkdown is the capacity to create fully reproducible results reporting. In the documetn below, we look at some of hte ways we can format text and output in Rmd, and how we can even write our results sections in Rmd, with results reported automatically and thus eliminating simple copying errors when transferring from statsitical software to Word. It also saves time when a slight change in the data (e.g.you collected extra cases, or spotted and error or duplicate) means you need to update all your statisical results and means etc.

(It is even possible to write whole papers in Rmd, see the end for an example.)

Set up

Ordinarily, we set our setup chunk to include=FALSE so that it isnt reproduced in the resulting html. However, it is included here.

We can use knitr in setup to give defaults for all chunks like this. It includes the option to show or hide all code in the rest of the document (echo).

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = TRUE,   #show code in knitted document
                      warning = TRUE,  #include any warnings
                      message = TRUE, #include any messages
                      fig.align = TRUE,   #sets figure options for all chunks
                      fig.width = 7,
                      fig.height = 7)

Headings

Use # followed by a space to indicate heading levels - # for level 1, ## for level 2 etc. This is particularly useful as we can set the YAML code in the header to automatically number sections in the html.

This is level 1

This is level 2

This is level 3

Making a list

Single lists

We can use asterisks followed by a space to make a bullet-pointed list. This list also includes code for embedding urls (text in () and url in []).

  • Reproducible workflows in Data Skills for Reproducible Science
  • R Markdown Cheatsheet
  • Stub script for this lesson

Making a lower level list

We can make multi level lists by adding in two spaces to lower level items like this:

  • Tidyr
    • Pipes
    • Gather
  • Lmer

Images

Use ! to tell Rmd to insert an image. Use [] to put in caption, and () to give the image location relative to the page.

Here is the image caption

We can also add images inside code chunks. Put echo = FALSE in the chunk header to stop it displaying once the document is knitted. We can change alignment for figures within a chunk in the chunk header (which overrides the general options above.)

Tables

Using pipes, we can load and process a dataset in order to get summary tables for scores weve calculated as part of the processing. In this example, we use the disgust dataset again. We get means and SDs by making the data long, generating summary scores for each pp for each domain, then regrouping by domain, and calculating domain means/sd.

disgust <- read_csv("data/disgust.csv")%>%
  gather(question, score, moral1:pathogen7) %>%
  separate(question, into = c("domain", "n"), sep=-1) %>%
  group_by(user_id,domain) %>%
  summarise(score = mean(score, na.rm = T)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  group_by(domain) %>%
  summarise(mean= mean(score, na.rm = T),
            sd = sd(score, na.rm = T)) %>%
  mutate_if(is.numeric, round,2)

The kable function can print the table in a more editable format.

knitr::kable(disgust) #can add e.g. digits=3 to specify number of dp if needed.
domain mean sd
moral 3.80 1.27
pathogen 3.73 1.06
sexual 2.57 1.36

Inline code and emphases

We can set up Rmd to report results from our analysis code into the text using backtick-r-space before, and backtick after. In the text below, I call the values assigned to the mean of each variable

moral_mean <- disgust %>% filter(domain=="moral") %>% pull(mean)
sexual_mean <- disgust %>% filter(domain=="sexual") %>% pull(mean)
path_mean <- disgust %>% filter(domain=="pathogen") %>% pull(mean)

ms <- disgust %>% filter(domain=="moral") %>% pull(sd)
ss <- disgust %>% filter(domain=="sexual") %>% pull(sd)
ps <- disgust %>% filter(domain=="pathogen") %>% pull(sd)

The mean score for moral disgust was 3.8 (SD = 1.27). The mean for sexual disgust was 2.57 (SD = 1.36) and for pathogen disgust it was 3.73 (SD = 1.06).

I just used asterisks to italicise words, double asterisks to bold, and you can use three asterisks to do both.

Citations

Add inline citations using square brackets and @ the name of the reference in your bibtex file. Also add bibliography: nameofbibtexfile in the YAML header. It will look like this:

We used Tidyverse (Wickham 2017).

If you just want the year, you can add a - in front of the @ like this: We used Wickham (2017).

Additional resources

Lisa DeBruine and Dale Barr have written a whole paper using Rmd and the papaja package (which gives more options for the YAML header, and is really good for academic papers. There are papaja template file you can use which helps with this.) You can find the Rmd file of their paper via her github repository. The paper in pdf form is currently posted on PsyarXiv, while in submission to AMPS.
